<B>Interval Estimates</B>
<Br>It is good practice to summarise your data by presenting interval estimates for the important parameters ( eg the mean <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#109;</FONT>
 ).   The interval should be accompanied by the probability that the interval will contain the parameter.

<P>The probability is the <B>level of confidence</B> and the resulting interval is called a <B>confidence interval</B>.

<Br>Generally we give a 95% confidence interval but sometimes a 90% or 99% interval is required.</p>


<UL>Try <a href="launch.htm#q0777">q0777</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0778">q0778</a>.</UL>

<HR>
<B>Estimating Sample Size</B> How do we know what size of sample to take to estimate the true mean of a population? Too small a sample size will lead to a poor estimate of the mean, and a needlessly large sample could waste time and money.
<UL>Try <a href="launch.htm#q0779">q0779</a>.</UL>
