<B>The t-distribution
</B>
<Br>In practice, we rarely know the value of <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#115;</FONT>
.   What we do when <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#115;</FONT>
 is <B>unknown</B> is to estimate it using the sample standard deviation <B>s</B></P>

<P>If we use <B>s instead of <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#115;</FONT>
 </B>, the z-statistic that we use to calculate confidence intervals becomes a 
<UL><B>‘t-statistic with n-1 degrees of freedom’</B>. </UL>  Often the Greek letter <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#110;</FONT>
 is used to denote degrees of freedom.</P>

<UL><LI>The t-distribution is actually a family of distributions since there is a different distribution for each value of <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#110;</FONT>
.  
<LI>The t-distribution is very similar to the Normal distribution.   As the degrees of freedom (= n-1) increase the percentage points become closer to the equivalent points from the Normal distribution. </UL>

